Another example is a little long to be quoted here, but it is in the last chapters of Mosiah and the first few chapters of Alma in the BoM.  But to summarize, this is one of the key verses that talks about the way that we are to treat each other despite differences  Alma 1:21 : Now there was a strict law among the people of the church that there should not any man, belnging to the church arise and persecute those that did not belong to the church, and that there should not be any persecutions among themselves.<br>
<br>
Several other references : 2Nephi:2:27  &quot;Wherefore men are free according to the flesh and all things are given them which are expedient unto man.  And they are free to choose...&quot;  This is not saying that all roads lead to Rome, but that God is not going to force us into believing or having faith.  We are free to choose whatever life we want to live.  Now the LDS differ a little from other Christian sects in that we believe that we are responsible for our choices.  If we choose to repent, Christs blood will atone for our mistakes, but that doesnt give us license to repeat the mistake or continue in sin.  We think that repentence is an ongoing process and that we arent &quot;saved&quot; until we endure to the end doing our darnedest to keep the commandments for all of our lives.<br>
