My guess is that you are implying that Mormons are forced to believe and act a certain way without choice?  If that is the implication you are sorely mistaken.  Our church is all about choice.  You either accept the doctrine or you dont, no one forces you.  Now if you mean that members dont have input on the doctrine, well you are right. God gives the doctrine and we either accept it or not, its entirely up to you.  Now if you want to believe or act in a way that is contrary to specific moral codes ( no adultry, no sex before marriage, no homosexual activity) and still be a member, you may not be given that choice.  <br>
<br>
Or if you think that the doctrine is wrong and you start preaching out publically about how wrong the doctrine is, you may be excommunicated its true. But then again, why would an individual want to belong to a church that they think is teching false doctrine.  If you are a member of this church you believe that God inspires his prophet and that the Prophet is the mouthpiece of the Lord.  If you dont buy that, then you are free to find a church where you feel more comfortable with the doctrine. <br>
<br>
Nobody knocks on my door to ask if Ive paid my tithing, no one asks me if Im living the word of wisdom unless I choose to go to the temple.  And I am aware of the temple recommend requirements so its not a suprise, I make the appointment I go talk to the bishop, no ones coercing me to do anything.  I dont have to turn in a log of missionary time or how many hours I spend reading the scriptures.<br>
<br>
Now I do know a few parents who forced their kids to church, but I dont know of any other person who is being forced or coerced into being a member or living by its teachings.<br>
